   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_XX_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1819-04">April 1819</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                            My dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">Mother,</persName><lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is well. We have<lb/>
                    just been at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Harley-Street_ENK">Harley S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
               </placeName>.<lb/>
                    Received your last letters<lb/>
                    I read your note to <del>J</del>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL2">LW</persName>.<lb/>
                    - This parting gave him<lb/>
                    exquisite pain - He <choice>
                  <orig>be-<lb/>
                        haved</orig>
                  <reg>behaved</reg>
               </choice> admirably well<lb/>
                    - my last words to him<lb/>
                    were <del>You</del> "I think you<lb/>
                    will find <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName>. &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrF1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Carrs</persName>
               <lb/>
                    family and the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs.</hi> Baillies</persName>
               <lb/>
                    prepared to receive you<lb/>
                    kindly &amp; I hope you will<lb/>
                    cultivate that society <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <del>There as</del> "Nothing shall<lb/>
                     be wanting on my part<lb/>
                    but there are two words<lb/>
                    to that bargain"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> Yes - One is already<lb/>
                     said &amp; settled for you<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_XX_page02.jpg"/>
            <lb/>
            <p> He then asked if we <choice>
                  <orig>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg/>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
                    like to have little <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxF4">F</persName>? for<lb/>
                    the Easter holidays at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep<lb/>
                        Dene</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    
                    If you would I will bring<lb/>
                    him to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dorking_ENK">Dorking</placeName> - I will not<lb/>
                    come amongst you - I will<lb/>
                    not come nearer to you<lb/>
                    - I only wish you &amp; your sister<lb/>
                    to have the pleasure <unclear>~</unclear>
               <lb/>
                    and I will take him back<lb/>
                    again from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dorking_ENK">Dorking</placeName> whenever<lb/>
                    you appoint <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>"I thank you for the<lb/>
                     generosity of this offer but<lb/>
                    I cannot accept it at the<lb/>
                    expense of the pain it<lb/>
                    would give you."<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  I Then shook hands<lb/>
                    with him &amp; said - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL2">M. Wilson</persName>
               <lb/>
                    at parting from you I<lb/>
                    can truly say you have<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_XX_page03.jpg"/>    
                    my perfect goodwill"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Indeed I pity him from<lb/>
                     my soul &amp; wish him<lb/>
                    every good but <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>
               <lb/>
                     whom we rejoice to<lb/>
                    have safe<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I write from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrR1">Lord Carrington</persName>
               <lb/>
                      study <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#White-Hall_ENK">White Hall</placeName> on<lb/>
                      my way to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep Dene</placeName>
               <lb/>
                      Where we dine &amp; I fear<lb/>
                    shall not be till <unclear>1/2</unclear> after<lb/>
                      6 - they dine at 7.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>We have appointed
                     to be at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#High-Wycombe_ENK">High Wycombe</placeName>
               <lb/>
                     1st of May &amp; <add>I</add> have <choice>
                  <orig>pro-<lb/>
                        mised</orig>
                  <reg>promised</reg>
               </choice> not to engage<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">when</hi> we shall have<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrR1">Lord <choice>
                     <orig>C</orig>
                     <reg>Carrington</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName>till we get there<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
                    No more <hi rend="underline">possible</hi>
               <lb/>
               from your <choice>
                  <orig>affec</orig>
                  <reg>affectionate</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">ME</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
